{"title_page": "Columbian College of Arts and Sciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Columbian College<br>of Arts & Sciences\n| image = Columbian College of Arts & Sciences logo.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| motto = Deus Nobis Fiducia <br/> (''In God Our Trust'')\n| established = 1821\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| dean = Paul Whalbeck\n| faculty = 1,007\n| undergrad = 4,933\n| postgrad = 1,763\n| doctoral = 861\n| address = 801 22nd St. NW\n| city = [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]\n| state = [[Washington, D.C.|D.C.]], 20052\n| campus = Urban\u2014[[Foggy Bottom]]\n| nickname = \n| parent = [[George Washington University]]\n| website = {{url|http://columbian.gwu.edu}}\n| logo = \n}}\n\nThe '''Columbian College of Arts and Sciences''' (known as '''Columbian College''' or '''CCAS''') is the [[College of Arts and Sciences|college of liberal arts and sciences]] of the [[George Washington University]], in [[Washington, D.C.]] The Columbian College is especially known for its programs in [[political sciences]], [[history]], [[English studies|English]], and [[economics]] in the [[United States]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nCCAS is the largest school at George Washington University, with around 5,000 undergraduate students and 2,500 graduate students, and 42 academic departments, representing a significant portion of the University's instructional, scholarly and research activity.\n\nThe college is known for its numerous prominent alumni, particularly in the fields of [[government]], [[economic development]], and [[public policy]], including notable living figures, such as [[Anwar Gargash]] (current [[Cabinet of the United Arab Emirates|Minister of State for Foreign Affairs]] of the [[United Arab Emirates]]), sitting [[U.S. Senator]] [[Mark Warner]], [[Vincent C. Gray]] (former [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]) and [[Daniel Weiss (art historian)|Daniel Weiss]] (CEO of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]). Historical alumni include [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] and [[Ralph Asher Alpher]], \"father of the [[Big Bang theory]]\".\n\n==History==\n[[File:Old Main Career Center GWU.JPG|thumb|left|The Old Main Building]]\n[[File:University Yard, George Washington University, 2012.JPG|thumb|right|University Yard, with [[Jean-Antoine Houdon]]'s statue, ''[[George Washington (Houdon)|George Washington]]'']]\nThe Columbian College of Arts and Sciences is the original college of George Washington University and one of the oldest colleges in the [[United States]]. It was  created as a Baptist institution by Reverend [[Luther Rice]], and officially founded as the Columbian College on February 9, 1821 by an [[act of Congress]] signed by President [[James Monroe]].<ref name=\"A Brief History of GW\">{{cite web |url= http://encyclopedia.gwu.edu/index.php?title=A_Brief_History_of_GW |title= A Brief History of GW |accessdate= 2014-07-31}}</ref> Originally, the college consisted of two departments: the Theological Department and Classical Department, with individual professors covering other subjects such as [[mathematics]] and [[anatomy]].\n\nThe college's first class graduated in 1824, where the president presented each of the three graduates with their degree in the presence of the [[Marquis de Lafayette]] and college president [[William Staughton]].<ref name=\"A Brief History of GW\"/>\n\nThe college conferred its first Master of Arts degree in 1831. It was one of the first institutions in the United States to award a doctorate, awarding a Doctor of Philosophy degree in 1888. However, the graduate program was not formally established until 1905.<ref name=\"Academic Degrees\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~ccas/academics/index.html#degrees|title=Academic Degrees|accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref>\n\nWith the dawn of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in 1861, the majority of the students left the college to fight for the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], and the campus buildings were used as a hospital and barracks.  In 1873 the college becomes Columbian University and in 1904 the George Washington University was established by an Act of Congress, with Columbian College and its Graduate School being integrated in the Department of Arts and Sciences.\n\nIn 1962 Columbian College changed its name to the Columbian College of Arts and Sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/about-us|title=About Columbian College {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:RomeHallPath.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Rome and Phillips Halls walkway with [[Gelman Library]] in the background.]]\nThe College contains many research centers and institutes, including the [[George Washington University Biostatistics Center|Biostatistics Center]]. Its main facilities are located at [[George Washington University]]'s [[Foggy Bottom]] [[George Washington University#Foggy Bottom|campus]].\n\n== Organization and administration ==\nThe college is managed by a team of administrative staff currently led by Interim Dean [[Paul Wahlbeck]] and Vice Dean [[Eric Arnesen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/who-we-are|title=Who We Are {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/meet-dean|title=Meet the Dean {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe  leadership is also supported by the National Council for Arts and Sciences, which  is composed of national and international alumni and others associated to the college, and serves a volunteer advisory board. Other affiliated advisory councils are the Corcoran Strategic Advisory Council, the National Council for Media and Public Affairs and the Trachtenberg School Advisory Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/national-council-arts-and-sciences|title=National Council for Arts & Sciences {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\n[[File:Corcoran School at GWU.tif|thumb|left|upright|The [[Corcoran School of the Arts and Design|Corcoran School of the Arts & Design]], across [[The Ellipse]] from the [[White House]].]]\nThe  Columbian College houses 42 academic departments  and programs. CCAS is also host to three distinct schools:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/what-we-do|title=What We Do {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n*[[George Washington University School of Media and Public Affairs|School of Media and Public Affairs]] (SMPA)\n*[[Corcoran School of the Arts and Design]]\n*[[Trachtenberg School of Public Policy and Public Administration]] (SPPPA)\n\nIt offers a total of 61 undergraduate minors, 58 undergraduate major, 51 master's degrees and 33 combined degree program's (bachelor's and master's).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/undergraduate-applicants|title=Undergraduate Applicants {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/special-interdisciplinary-major|title=Special Interdisciplinary Major {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> The College offers degrees in the main fields Arts & Design, Clinical Programs, Humanities, Mathematics & Statistical Analysis, Natural & Forensic Sciences, Policy & Public Affairs and Social & Behavioral Sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/departments-programs|title=Departments and Programs {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe college also offers different engaged learning programs, an extensive on- and offline summer school program, 16 graduate certificates and more than 30 doctoral degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/engaged-learning-opportunities|title=Engaged Learning Opportunities {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/graduate-certificates|title=Graduate Certificates {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/doctoral-degrees|title=Doctoral Degrees {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe college has an international network of partnering universities and schools. For students there are currently more than 300 study and exchange programs in 50 countries available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studyabroad.gwu.edu/approved-program-options|title=Approved Program Options {{!}} Office for Study Abroad {{!}} The George Washington University|website=studyabroad.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center; | <big>Columbian College rankings</big>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center; background-color:#E6E6FA\" | World rankings\n|-\n| '''''[[Academic Ranking of World Universities|ARWU]]'''''<ref>[http://www.shanghairanking.com/shanghairanking-subject-rankings/political-sciences.html ARWU - Political sciences]</ref> \u2013 [[Political science]]\n| 17th\n|-\n| '''''[[QS World University Rankings|QS]]'''''<ref>[https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2018/politics QS World University Rankings - Politics]</ref>  \u2013 [[Political science]]\n| 22nd\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center; background-color:#E6E6FA\" | U.S. rankings\n|-\n| '''''[[U.S. News & World Report|U.S. News & World]]''''' \u2013 [[History]]\n| 59th\n|-\n| '''''[[U.S. News & World Report|U.S. News & World]]''''' \u2013 [[Economics]]\n| 63rd\n|-\n|}\n\nThe  College is ranked as the 7th best college of [[political sciences]] in the United States, by ''[[USA Today|USA Today College rankings]]''.<ref>[http://college.usatoday.com/2016/11/04/best-colleges-for-political-science/ USA Today College - Best Colleges for Political Sciences]</ref>\n\nIn the ''2018 [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]'', Columbian ranks in the top 76-100 schools of [[social sciences]] in the world.<ref>[http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldSOC2016.html ARWU - Global Social Sciences Rankings]</ref>\n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks its graduate programs as:\n\n* History, 59th best in the United States\n* Economics, 63rd best in the United States\n* English, 67th best in the United States\n\n== Research ==\nThe  College is home to 28 research centers and institutes with an average annual research expenditure of $18.6 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/research|title=Research & Discovery {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/centers-institutes|title=Centers & Institutes {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref> Research is supported by  internal funding and external grants from institutions like the National Science Foundation and the National Institutes of Health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/faculty-research|title=Faculty Research {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIt also offers different undergraduate, graduate and postdoctoral student research fellowships and programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/student-research|title=Student Research {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of Columbian College of Arts and Sciences people}}\n<gallery heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Notable Alumni of the Columbian College\">\nFile:Mrs Kennedy in the Diplomatic Reception Room cropped.jpg|[[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] ('51) - [[First Lady of the United States]] \nFile:DanWeiss photo (cropped).png|[[Daniel Weiss (art historian)|Daniel H. Weiss]] ('79) - President & CEO the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\nFile:Eric_Cantor,_official_113th_Congress_photo_portrait.jpg|[[Eric Cantor]] ('85) - Former [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Majority Leader]]\nFile:Mark Warner 113th Congress photo.jpg|[[Mark Warner]] ('77) - Current [[U.S. senator|U.S. Senator]] and former [[Governor of Virginia]]\nFile:Anwar Gargash.jpg|[[Anwar Gargash]] ('81, '84) - [[Cabinet of the United Arab Emirates|Minister of State for Foreign Affairs]] of the [[United Arab Emirates]]\nFile:Mayor Vincent Gray Talks About Consumer Protection (6918837914) (cropped).jpg|[[Vincent C. Gray]] ('64) - Former [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]\nFile:Steve_Israel_113th_Congress.jpg|[[Steve Israel]] ('81) - Former Chair of the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]]\nFile:Kerry Washington Django avp.jpg|[[Kerry Washington]] ('98) - [[Time 100]] and [[Emmy Award]]-winning actress\nFile:Huma_Abedin_DNC_2016_Pre_Hillary_Clinton_Speech_at_Democratic_National_Convention_(July_28,_2016).jpg|[[Huma Abedin]] ('97) - Former [[chief of staff]] to [[Hillary Clinton]]\nFile:Carl_Lutz_fortepan_105824.jpg|[[Carl Lutz]] ('24) - Swiss diplomat who saved over 62,000 Jews during [[World War II]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://columbian.gwu.edu/}}\n\n{{GWU}}\n\n{{coord|38|53|59.7|N|77|2|53.4|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Columbian College Of Arts And Sciences}}\n[[Category:Colleges and Schools of The George Washington University]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges at universities in the United States]]\n[[Category:1821 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Columbian College of Arts and Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Columbian College<br>of Arts & Sciences\n| image = Columbian College of Arts & Sciences logo.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| motto = Deus Nobis Fiducia <br/> (''In God Our Trust'')\n| established = 1821\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| dean = Paul Whalbeck\n| faculty = 1,007\n| undergrad = 4,933\n| postgrad = 1,763\n| doctoral = 861\n| address = 801 22nd St. NW\n| city = [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]\n| state = [[Washington, D.C.|D.C.]], 20052\n| campus = Urban\u2014[[Foggy Bottom]]\n| nickname = \n| parent = [[George Washington University]]\n| website = {{url|http://columbian.gwu.edu}}\n| logo = \n}}\n\nThe '''Columbian College of Arts and Sciences''' (known as '''Columbian College''' or '''CCAS''') is the [[College of Arts and Sciences|college of liberal arts and sciences]] of the [[George Washington University]], in [[Washington, D.C.]] The Columbian College is especially known for its programs in [[political sciences]], [[history]], [[English studies|English]], and [[economics]] in the [[United States]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n\nCCAS is the largest school at George Washington University, with around 5,000 undergraduate students and 2,500 graduate students, and 42 academic departments, representing a significant portion of the University's instructional, scholarly and research activity.\n\nThe college is known for its numerous prominent alumni, particularly in the fields of [[government]], [[economic development]], and [[public policy]], including notable living figures, such as [[Anwar Gargash]] (current [[Cabinet of the United Arab Emirates|Minister of State for Foreign Affairs]] of the [[United Arab Emirates]]), sitting [[U.S. Senator]] [[Mark Warner]], [[Vincent C. Gray]] (former [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]) and [[Daniel Weiss (art historian)|Daniel Weiss]] (CEO of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]). Historical alumni include [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] and [[Ralph Asher Alpher]], \"father of the [[Big Bang theory]]\".\n\n==History==\n[[File:Old Main Career Center GWU.JPG|thumb|left|The Old Main Building]]\n[[File:University Yard, George Washington University, 2012.JPG|thumb|right|University Yard, with [[Jean-Antoine Houdon]]'s statue, ''[[George Washington (Houdon)|George Washington]]'']]\nThe Columbian College of Arts and Sciences is the original college of George Washington University and one of the oldest colleges in the [[United States]]. It was  created as a Baptist institution by Reverend [[Luther Rice]], and officially founded as the Columbian College on February 9, 1821 by an [[act of Congress]] signed by President [[James Monroe]].<ref name=\"A Brief History of GW\">{{cite web |url= http://encyclopedia.gwu.edu/index.php?title=A_Brief_History_of_GW |title= A Brief History of GW |accessdate= 2014-07-31}}</ref> Originally, the college consisted of two departments: the Theological Department and Classical Department, with individual professors covering other subjects such as [[mathematics]] and [[anatomy]]. \n\nThe college's first class graduated in 1824, where the president presented each of the three graduates with their degree in the presence of the [[Marquis de Lafayette]] and college president [[William Staughton]].<ref name=\"A Brief History of GW\"/>\n\nThe college conferred its first Master of Arts degree in 1831. It was one of the first institutions in the United States to award a doctorate, awarding a Doctor of Philosophy degree in 1888. However, the graduate program was not formally established until 1905.<ref name=\"Academic Degrees\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gwu.edu/~ccas/academics/index.html#degrees|title=Academic Degrees|accessdate=2009-06-20}}</ref>\n\nWith the dawn of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in 1861, the majority of the students left the college to fight for the [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]], and the campus buildings were used as a hospital and barracks.  In 1873 the college becomes Columbian University and in 1904 the George Washington University was established by an Act of Congress, with Columbian College and its Graduate School being integrated in the Department of Arts and Sciences.\n\nIn 1962 Columbian College changed its name to the Columbian College of Arts and Sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/about-us|title=About Columbian College {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:RomeHallPath.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Rome and Phillips Halls walkway with [[Gelman Library]] in the background.]]\nThe College contains many research centers and institutes, including the [[George Washington University Biostatistics Center|Biostatistics Center]]. Its main facilities are located at [[George Washington University]]'s [[Foggy Bottom]] [[George Washington University#Foggy Bottom|campus]].\n\n== Organization and administration ==\nThe college is managed by a team of administrative staff currently led by Interim Dean [[Paul Wahlbeck]] and Vice Dean [[Eric Arnesen]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/who-we-are|title=Who We Are {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/meet-dean|title=Meet the Dean {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>  \n\nThe  leadership is also supported by the National Council for Arts and Sciences, which  is composed of national and international alumni and others associated to the college, and serves a volunteer advisory board. Other affiliated advisory councils are the Corcoran Strategic Advisory Council, the National Council for Media and Public Affairs and the Trachtenberg School Advisory Board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/national-council-arts-and-sciences|title=National Council for Arts & Sciences {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\n[[File:Corcoran School at GWU.tif|thumb|left|upright|The [[Corcoran School of the Arts and Design|Corcoran School of the Arts & Design]], across [[The Ellipse]] from the [[White House]].]]\nThe  Columbian College houses 42 academic departments  and programs. CCAS is also host to three distinct schools:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/what-we-do|title=What We Do {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n*[[George Washington University School of Media and Public Affairs|School of Media and Public Affairs]] (SMPA)\n*[[Corcoran School of the Arts and Design]]\n*[[Trachtenberg School of Public Policy and Public Administration]] (SPPPA)\n\nIt offers a total of 61 undergraduate minors, 58 undergraduate major, 51 master's degrees and 33 combined degree program's (bachelor's and master's).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/undergraduate-applicants|title=Undergraduate Applicants {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/special-interdisciplinary-major|title=Special Interdisciplinary Major {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> The College offers degrees in the main fields Arts & Design, Clinical Programs, Humanities, Mathematics & Statistical Analysis, Natural & Forensic Sciences, Policy & Public Affairs and Social & Behavioral Sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/departments-programs|title=Departments and Programs {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe college also offers different engaged learning programs, an extensive on- and offline summer school program, 16 graduate certificates and more than 30 doctoral degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/engaged-learning-opportunities|title=Engaged Learning Opportunities {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/graduate-certificates|title=Graduate Certificates {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/doctoral-degrees|title=Doctoral Degrees {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe college has an international network of partnering universities and schools. For students there are currently more than 300 study and exchange programs in 50 countries available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studyabroad.gwu.edu/approved-program-options|title=Approved Program Options {{!}} Office for Study Abroad {{!}} The George Washington University|website=studyabroad.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center; | <big>Columbian College rankings</big>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center; background-color:#E6E6FA\" | World rankings\n|-\n| '''''[[Academic Ranking of World Universities|ARWU]]'''''<ref>[http://www.shanghairanking.com/shanghairanking-subject-rankings/political-sciences.html ARWU - Political sciences]</ref> \u2013 [[Political science]]\n| 17th\n|-\n| '''''[[QS World University Rankings|QS]]'''''<ref>[https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2018/politics QS World University Rankings - Politics]</ref>  \u2013 [[Political science]]\n| 22nd\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center; background-color:#E6E6FA\" | U.S. rankings\n|-\n| '''''[[U.S. News & World Report|U.S. News & World]]''''' \u2013 [[History]]\n| 59th\n|-\n| '''''[[U.S. News & World Report|U.S. News & World]]''''' \u2013 [[Economics]]\n| 63rd\n|-\n|}\n\nThe  College is ranked as the 7th best college of [[political sciences]] in the United States, by ''[[USA Today|USA Today College rankings]]''.<ref>[http://college.usatoday.com/2016/11/04/best-colleges-for-political-science/ USA Today College - Best Colleges for Political Sciences]</ref> \n\nIn the ''2018 [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]'', Columbian ranks in the top 76-100 schools of [[social sciences]] in the world.<ref>[http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldSOC2016.html ARWU - Global Social Sciences Rankings]</ref>  \n\n''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks its graduate programs as:\n\n* History, 59th best in the United States\n* Economics, 63rd best in the United States\n* English, 67th best in the United States\n\n== Research ==\nThe  College is home to 28 research centers and institutes with an average annual research expenditure of $18.6 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/research|title=Research & Discovery {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/centers-institutes|title=Centers & Institutes {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref> Research is supported by  internal funding and external grants from institutions like the National Science Foundation and the National Institutes of Health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/faculty-research|title=Faculty Research {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref> \n\nIt also offers different undergraduate, graduate and postdoctoral student research fellowships and programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbian.gwu.edu/student-research|title=Student Research {{!}} Columbian College of Arts & Sciences  {{!}} The George Washington University|website=columbian.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of Columbian College of Arts and Sciences people}}\n<gallery heights=\"150\" mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Notable Alumni of the Columbian College\">\nFile:Mrs Kennedy in the Diplomatic Reception Room cropped.jpg|[[Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis]] ('51) - [[First Lady of the United States]] \nFi