ortant business and financial areas in the metropolis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/profile/index.aspx|title=Mandaluyong City Profile |accessdate=9 February 2014 |publisher=City Government of Mandaluyong}}</ref>\n\n=== Commercial activities===\n[[File:Mandaluyong skyline (from Mezza 2) (Mandaluyong)(2018-05-12).jpg|thumb|right|The Mandaluyong City Skyline excluding [[Ortigas Center]].]]\nLike other cities in [[Metro Manila]], Mandaluyong has its own share of commercial strips and a central business district.\nThe former commercial area, consisting mostly of banks, offices and service establishments, stretch along public transport routes thereby serving both local consumers and passers-by from the neighboring localities.\nMajor commercial strips of the city include the stretch of [[Boni Avenue]], [[Shaw Boulevard]], Libertad-Sierra Madre area, Kalentong, San Francisco, part of Martinez, Sgt. Bumatay towards Barangka Drive and Pinatubo towards [[EDSA (road)|EDSA]]. Mandaluyong's central business district is concentrated on the EDSA-Shaw-Pioneer area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/profile/economy.aspx|title=Commercial Activities |accessdate=9 February 2014 |publisher=City Government of Mandaluyong}}</ref>\n\n===Industrial activities===\n[[File:TV5 Media Center - reliance side (Reliance cor. Sheridan, Mandaluyong; 2017-01-06).jpg|thumb|right|[[TV5 Media Center]]]]\nIndustrial activities are mostly concentrated within the [[Shaw Boulevard]]-[[Pioneer Street|Pioneer area]] and along the [[Pasig River]]. Although prominent in the manufacture of foods, medicines and laboratory equipment, these industries are gradually declining in number, opting to relocate in newly developed industrial zones outside Metropolitan Manila. In the [[Pasig River]] area, particularly in Barangays Namayan and Mabini J. Rizal, areas formerly industrial are now the sites for residential subdivisions and townhouses. In the EDSA-Shaw-Pioneer area, the transformation is toward a more economically profitable and globally competitive commercial activity. And since December 2013, Mandaluyong is the home of one of the largest television networks in the country, [[The 5 Network]] (owned by [[TV5 Network]] located at the [[TV5 Media Center]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/profile/economy.aspx|title=Industrial Activities |accessdate=9 February 2014 |publisher=City Government of Mandaluyong}}</ref>\n\n===Shopping centers===\nThese super-regional supermalls each have over a hundred local and international stores and are anchored by at least one department store and supermarket or hypermarket. They are also the largest malls in Metro Manila which feature not just stores but also attractions: movie theaters, rides, skating rinks, bowling alleys and other recreational facilities. Each provides thousands of automobile parking spaces and are located mostly near [[List of Manila LRT and MRT stations|rail stations]] and established [[business district]]s within the metropolis. These malls serve not only the Metro Manila and Greater Manila Area residents, but also local and foreign tourists. Among the malls in the city are [[Shangri-La Plaza Mall|Shangri-La Plaza]] and [[SM Megamall]]\n\n==Local government==\n[[2019 Philippine local elections|2019 Philippine local election]] results:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ph.rappler.com/local/region/Metro-Manila/Mandaluyong-City |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001155159/http://ph.rappler.com/local/region/Metro-Manila/Mandaluyong-City |archive-date=1 October 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position\n! Candidate\n! Party\n! Total Votes\n|-\n| Representative<br />{{small|''Lone Legislative District''}}\n| [[Neptali Gonzales II]]\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 127,268\n|-\n| Mayor\n| [[Carmelita Abalos]]\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 128,661\n|-\n| Vice Mayor\n| Antonio Suva Jr.\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 111,922\n|-\n| rowspan=15 | City Councilors\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{small|'''1st Sanggunian District'''}}\n|-\n| Charisse Marie Abalos-Vargas\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 73,915\n|-\n| Anjelo Elton Yap\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 58,272\n|-\n| Danilo De Guzman \n| [[Aksyon Demokratiko|Aksyon]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 54,690\n|-\n| Grace Marie Antonio\n| [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 54,221\n|-\n| Rodolfo Posadas\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 54,057\n|-\n| Estanislao Alim\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 44,525\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center;\"| {{small|'''2nd Sanggunian District'''}}\n|-\n| Benjamin Abalos III\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 44,636\n|-\n| Cherry Lynn Pablo-Santos\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 42,035\n|-\n| Roehl Bacar \n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 40,653\n|-\n| Jesus Cruz\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 40,288\n|-\n| Fernando Ocampo\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 40,172\n|-\n| Michael Gonzales-Cuejilo\n| [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP\u2013Laban]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 29,089\n|}\n\n===Mayors of Mandaluyong===\n\nListed below are persons who have served as mayors of Mandaluyong.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name  \n! Term\n|-\n| Buenaventrura Domingo\n| 1901 \n|-\n| Antonio Fernando\n| 1902\n|-\n| Juanario Coronado\n| 1902; 1909; 1912\n|-\n| Miguel Vergara\n| 1902\n|-\n| Pantaleon Blas \n| 1903\n|-\n| Claro Casta\u00f1eda \n| 1905\n|-\n| Apolinar Coronado\n| 1907; 1909\n|-\n| Marcelo Lerma\n| 1912\u20131916\n|-\n| Mariano Casta\u00f1eda\n| 1916\u20131922\n|-\n| Gregorio Pedro\n| 1923\u20131926\n|-\n| Clemente Fernando\n| 1926\u20131934\n|-\n| Isaac Lopez\n| 1935\u20131939\n|-\n| Ponciano Enriquez\n| 1940\n|-\n| Pedro Cruz\n| 1941; 1945; 1956 \u2013 1959\n|-\n| Primo Guzman\n| 1945\n|-\n| Bonifacio Javier\n| 1946; 1947 \u2013 1955; 1960 \u2013 1962\n|-\n| Amado T. Reyes\n| 1963\n|-\n| Filemon Javier\n| 1964\u20131971\n|-\n| Melchor Arcangel\n| 1963\n|-\n| Macario Trinidad\n| 1963\n|-\n| Renato Lopez\n| 1972\u20131980\n|-\n| Ernesto Domingo\n| 1980\u20131986\n|-\n| [[Benjamin Abalos|Benjamin S. Abalos, Sr.]](OIC)\n| 1986\u20131987\n|-\n| Roman delos Santos(OIC)\n| 1987\u20131988\n|-\n| [[Benjamin Abalos|Benjamin S. Abalos, Sr.]]\n| 1988\u20131998\n|-\n| [[Neptali M. Gonzales II]]\n| 2004\u20132007\n|-\n| [[Benjamin Abalos, Jr.|Benjamin S. Abalos, Jr.]]\n| 1998 \u2013 2004; 2007\u20132016\n|-\n| Carmelita Aguilar-Abalos\n| 2016\u2013present\n|}\n\n==Transportation==\n\n[[File:Mandaluyong City 2.JPG|thumbnail|[[Shaw Boulevard]], one of the major thoroughfares in the city]]\n\nThe city is provided with good access roads to and from adjacent cities in the metropolis. The city is served by one of [[Metro Manila]]'s main roads such as the [[Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]] (EDSA), [[Ortigas Avenue]] and [[Shaw Boulevard]].<ref name=\"Transportation\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/profile/infrastructure.aspx|title=Transportation |accessdate=10 February 2014 |publisher=City Government of Mandaluyong}}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\nThe city is 36 minutes away from the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]].\n\n===Land===\nMandaluyong is served by the [[Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]], Metro Manila's main thoroughfare.  Considered as the heart of the metropolis, main roads such as the [[Ortigas Avenue]] and [[Shaw Boulevard]] provide inter-city linkages, while [[Boni Avenue]] and Martinez Street (C-3 Road) serve as alternate routes in the city.<ref name=\"Transportation\"/> Other major roads in Mandaluyong include Boni-Pioneer Underpass, a 280-meter long tunnel underneath EDSA (Epifanio de los Santos Avenue) connecting Boni Avenue on its western-end and [[Pioneer Street]] on the east. and [[Julia Vargas Avenue]]. [[Jeepney]]s are one of the most common modes of public transportation for commuters in the city. Aside from jeepneys, tricycles and pedicabs are also one of the important modes of public transportation in Mandaluyong, especially on alleys around the city.\n\n===Water===\nThe presence of the [[Pasig River]] stretching along the south border of Mandaluyong provides an alternative route and mode of public transportation mainly for cargo freight of industries along the river, and for commuters seeking for a faster and more direct route to and from the cities of [[Pasig]] and [[Manila]].<ref name=\"Transportation\"/> The [[Pasig River Ferry Service]] has one station in the city.\n\n===Railway===\n\nThe city is also served by rail via the [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System Line 3]]. The line is located along the Epifanio de los Santos Avenue. The city is served by three Line 3 stations:\n\n*[[Ortigas MRT Station|Ortigas]]\n*[[Shaw Boulevard MRT Station|Shaw Boulevard]]\n*[[Boni MRT Station|Boni]]\n\n===Bridges===\n\nMandaluyong is accessed by [[Pasig River]] and [[San Juan River (Metro Manila)|San Juan River]]:\n\n{|| width=\"100%\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! Crossing\n! Carries\n! Image\n! Location\n! Built\n! Coordinates\n|-\n!colspan=7|\n'''Pasig River<br/>\nMakati \u2013 Mandaluyong\n|-\n| Makati\u2013Mandaluyong Bridge\n| [[Makati Avenue]] to Coronado Street\n| [[File:Pasig River Algae.jpg|70px]]\n| [[Makati Poblacion|Barangay Poblacion]] and Barangay Hulo\n|\n|{{coord|14.569354|N|121.031742|E}}\n|-\n| [[Estrella\u2013Pantaleon Bridge]]<br />''Rockwell Bridge''\n| [[Estrella Street]] to Pantaleon Street\n|<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:Estrella-Pantaleon Bridge.jpg|70px]] -->\n| [[Makati Poblacion|Barangay Poblacion]] and Barangay Hulo\n| 2011 (closed as of 2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/212896/news/nation/new-bridge-connecting-makati-mandaluyong-opened |title=New bridge connecting Makati, Mandaluyong opened |publisher=[[GMA Network News]] |accessdate=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n|{{coord|14.567408|N|121.037516|E}}\n|-\n| Guadalupe Bridge\n| [[Circumferential Road 4|C-4]]<br />[[EDSA (road)|Epifanio de los Santos Avenue]]\n| [[File:FvfGuadalupePasigRiver0074 35.JPG|70px]]\n| Brgys. Guadalupe Nuevo/Viejo and Barangay Barangka Ilaya\n| \n|{{coord|14.568466|N|121.045979|E}}\n|-\n| Line 3 Bridge\n|<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:MRT3Logo Sm.png|25px|25px]]  -->[[Manila Metro Rail Transit System Line 3]] (Line 3)\n| [[File:MRT-3 Tracks Guadalupe 6.jpg|70px]]\n| Brgys. Guadalupe Nuevo/Viejo and Barangay Barangka Ilaya\n|\n|{{coord|14.568466|N|121.045979|E}}\n|-\n!colspan=7|\n'''San Juan River<br/>\nManila \u2013 Mandaluyong\n|-\n| Sevilla Bridge\n| P. Sanchez Street to [[Shaw Boulevard]]\n|<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:Sevilla Bridge via Google Street View.png|75px]] -->\n| [[Santa Mesa|Santa Mesa District]] and Barangay Daang Bakal\n|\n|{{coord|14.595367|N|121.028065|E}}\n|-\n!colspan=7|\nSan Juan \u2013 Mandaluyong\n|-\n| Kalentong Bridge\n| F. Blumentritt Street to Gen. Kalentong Street\n|<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:Kalentong Bridge via Google Street View.png|70px]] -->\n| Barangay Kabayanan and Barangay Daang Bakal\n|\n|{{coord|14.593973|N|121.026128|E}}\n|}\n\n==Health==\n{{See also|List of hospitals in Metro Manila}}\nMandaluyong has several private and public hospitals & health center, namely the privately owned Dr. Victor R. Potenciano Medical Center along EDSA and Unciano General Hospital, and the government hospital Mandaluyong City Medical Center.  The city is also home to the [[National Center for Mental Health]]. Many residents, specifically the middle-to-upper class medical clientele, visit the nearby [[The Medical City]] in Ortigas Center.\n\nThe Dr. Victor R. Potenciano Medical Center is a tertiary care hospital that has a 189-bed capacity within its 10-storey hospital building.\n\nIn 2007, the Mandaluyong City government, together with [[non-governmental organization]] Rehabilitation and Empowerment of Adults and Children (REACH) Foundation, established a [[community-based rehabilitation]] program called Project Therapy, Education, and Assimilation of Children with Handicap (TEACH), that caters to children with special needs coming from indigent families. Services given by Project TEACH include free [[occupational therapy]], [[physical therapy]], [[speech-language pathology|speech therapy]] and [[special education]] classes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yee|first1=Jovic|title=Free school, therapy for poor kids with special needs wins UN award|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/123035/free-school-therapy-for-poor-kids-with-special-needs-wins-un-award|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=17 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\n[[File:LSGHcampus.jpg|thumb|St. Benilde Gymnasium in La Salle Green Hills]]\n\nFour well-known educational institutions in the city are the [[Arellano University|Arellano University, Mandaluyong (Plaridel Campus)]], [[Don Bosco Technical College]], [[Jose Rizal University]] and [[Rizal Technological University]].\n\nA good number of city officials of Mandaluyong are alumni of Don Bosco,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/updates/news/index.aspx?id=187 |title=City of Mandaluyong : News Updates |publisher=Mandaluyong.gov.ph |date=3 January 2011 |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> including incumbent Mayor, [[Benjamin Abalos, Jr.]] (HS '79);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bosco.arttickles.com/archives/letters-mar03-feb04.htm |title=Don Bosco High School |publisher=Bosco.arttickles.com |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> former Vice Mayor, Renato Santa Maria (HS '65);<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bicc.org.ph/pub/resources/temp_images/Don%20Bosco%2009%20FINAL.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910124949/http://www.bicc.org.ph/pub/resources/temp_images/Don%20Bosco%2009%20FINAL.pdf |archive-date=10 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> City Councilors Edward Bartolome (HS '96),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/govt/council.aspx?id=7 |title=Mandaluyong City Council : Edward Gabriel Bartolome |publisher=Mandaluyong.gov.ph |date=4 November 1979 |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> Noel Bernardo (HS '79),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/govt/council.aspx |title=Mandaluyong City Council |publisher=Mandaluyong.gov.ph |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> and Jonathan Abalos (HS '85).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.donboscoforum.com/index.php?threadid=1096;start=0 |title=www.donboscoforum.com |publisher=donboscoforum.com |accessdate=17 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519184556/http://www.donboscoforum.com/index.php?threadid=1096;start=0 |archive-date=19 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other notable alumni include \"King of Pinoy Rap,\" [[Francis Magalona]] (HS '81);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aboutmyrecovery.com/2009/03/06/francis-magalona-succumbs-to-cancer/ |title=Francis Magalona Succumbs to Cancer &#124; A Filipina Mom Blogger |publisher=Aboutmyrecovery.com |accessdate=17 October 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707121149/http://aboutmyrecovery.com/2009/03/06/francis-magalona-succumbs-to-cancer/ |archive-date=7 July 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and actor [[Ricky Davao]] (HS '78).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbase.com/rvicencio/dbmhs72 |title=Don Bosco Mandaluyong Batch 72 Photo Gallery by Jojo Vicencio \u2013 DU1VHY at |publisher=Pbase.com |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> Meanwhile, the alumni of JRU that includes President [[Ramon Magsaysay]], Roderick Paulate, and Secretary Armand V. Fabella; \nOther colleges in the city include the Our Lady of Guadalupe Colleges (specializing in Medicine and Nursing), STI and AMA (both specializing in Computer Technology education, both located on Shaw Boulevard), NAMEI Polytechnic Institute (specializing in Marine Sciences), and the International Baptist College.\n\nThe city is also home to [[Lourdes School of Mandaluyong]] (est. 1959), a [[Franciscan]]-Marian all-boys school, located in the [[Ortigas Center]] district managed by the [[OFM Capuchins]]; [[La Salle Green Hills]] (est. 1959), a private all-boys high school, managed by the [[De La Salle Brothers]], located along Ortigas Avenue; and [[Saint Pedro Poveda College]] (est. 1960), another all-girls institution, offering pre-school, grade school, high school, and college education. Although the official school address is Quezon City, part of the lot Poveda's campus stands on is under Mandaluyong City.\n\n[[Mandaluyong High School]] (est. 1977) is the oldest public high school in the city. [[City of Mandaluyong Science High School]] (est. 1996), a public science high school on E. Pantaleon St. The city has 18 public schools, including primary and secondary schools as prioritize by the city government. The Mataas Na Paaralang Nepatli A. Gonzales is the largest school in Mandaluyong and the only school in the city which has the STEM highschool program. The Neptalians are also multi- awarded and has various great observations by the regional supervisors that captures their attentions.\n\n==International relations==\n\n===Diplomatic missions===\n\nCountries that have set up permanent missions or embassies in the city include:\n\n*{{MLT}}\n*{{PER}}\n*{{SVN}}\n*{{SDN}}\n*{{TZA}}\n\n===Sister cities===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!National \n|- valign=\"top\"\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:110%;\"|\n* [[Legazpi, Albay]]\n* [[Silay, Negros Occidental]]\n* [[Tagum, Davao del Norte]]\n|}\n\n==Official march==\nThe official march of Mandaluyong is entitled \"Martsa ng Mandaluyong\" and was composed by then Councilor Delfin Asistio during the incumbency of then Mayor [[Benjamin Abalos]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of renamed cities and municipalities of the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mandaluyong City}}\n{{wikivoyage|Mandaluyong}}\n* [http://www.mandaluyong.gov.ph/ Mandaluyong] \u2013 Official city website\n* {{OSM relation|2284209}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n| North     = [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| West      = [[Manila]]\n| Center    = Mandaluyong\n| East      = [[Pasig]]\n| South     = [[Makati]]\n| Northeast = [[Quezon City]]\n}}\n\n{{Metro Manila}}\n{{Philippine cities}}\n{{Most populous cities in Philippines}}\n{{Largest Cities and Municipalities in Luzon}}\n\n[[Category:Mandaluyong| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1841]]\n[[Category:1841 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Pasig River]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = {{PH wikidata|name}}\n| official_name                   = City of Mandaluyong\n| image_skyline                   = City_of_Mandaluyong.png\n| image_caption                   = <small>From top, left to right: San Felipe Neri Church, Boni Avenue Skyline, [[SM Megamall]], Mandaluyong City Hall, Zumba dance</small>\n| image_flag                      = Flag of Mandaluyong.png\n| image_seal                      = Ph seal Mandaluyong.png\n| seal_size                       = 100x90px\n| motto                           